No longer an 'invisible man': #WestPoint to name new $186million #cadet barracks after black #graduate who was shunned by the entire #university... but went on to become the #first black #general of the #AirForce
By #AnnetaKonstantinides For #Dailymail.com and #AssociatedPress
17:25 EDT 10 May 2015, updated 17:42 EDT 10 May 2015

#BenjaminODavisJr. was the only black cadet at the #academy in 1932
He had no roommates or friends and was rarely even spoken to 
But Davis became one of the academy's most #accomplished graduates
He commanded the all-black #TuskegeeAirmen during #WorldWarII 
Davis retired a three-star general in 1970, was awarded a fourth in 1998 
Benjamin O. Davis Jr. was the only black cadet when he entered West Point in 1932. 
Davis spent his four years at the #military academy shunned, with no roommates or friends, in an experience he later said made him feel like 'an #invisible #man'. Now the university wants to #honor the man who went on to become one of its most accomplished graduates by naming a new $186m cadet barracks after Davis.

Previous graduates who have received the rare #privilege include #President #DwightDEisenhower and #fivestargeneral #DouglasMacArthur. 
But Davis proved he was much more than an 'invisible man' long before this honor came along. 
Davis, who passed away in 2002 at age 89, became the first black general of the Air Force. 
He commanded the all-black #332nd Fighter group, also known as the Tuskegee Airmen and the #RedTails, during World War II. 
They were the first #AfricanAmerican military #aviators in the #UnitedStatesArmedForces.

Ну что, сегодня закончились на отлично история, длиною в 8 лет!
Если бы я могла вернуться назад, в 2009, я бы посоветовала бы себе:
◾Смотреть ближе. То что надо практически всегда находится под носом.
◾ Изучать историю своей семьи.
◾ Концентрировать внимание на своем вузе,а не на соседних.
◾Не бояться сессий: будет очень страшно, но главное спать по ночам.
◾ Большие трагедии приносят большие удачи.
◾ Есть профессии, для которых говорить публично и учить — как дышать.
◾ Книги, как и многие вещи в этой жизни — интересно. Надо только понять методику и суть.
◾Вне зависимости от того, что говорят окружающие и вне зависимости от гендера и других параметров — YES, YOU CAN.
❔Вот мои восемь советов! А что бы вы отправили себе в 2009? Или, может, в 2007? 2004?

When I started this doctoral program 5 years ago, Regina Spektor’s album, What We Saw from the Cheap Seats, had just come out. I listened to it obsessively that first year, sang/yelled along to all the songs with my windows down on my hour long commute to and from campus, and found my anthem. Again and again, I’d sing the words to “Open,” let them run through me, will them to emanate out of me: “Potentially lovely/Perpetually human/Suspended and open” – an anthem that allowed me to be both exquisite and flawed, powerful and frail as I held my hands open and out, reaching fearfully, boldly for more of the wild unknown.
.
By the end of that first year, I was run-down, burnt-out, and ready to quit forever. I’d tried this suspended and open thing, and it was too hard. I told my therapist it was official – no more grad school. Almost on cue, this is the precise moment when everything started to click – when my friend sent me a disability studies article that made my heart pound (the kind of heart-pounding that comes when the earth shifts below and you realize you’ll never look at the world (or your own body) with the same eyes again), when I started reading disability memoirs and writing about my personal experiences, when one of my professors said, “Hey, you come alive when you talk about this stuff – maybe pay attention to that.” Things started to fit.
.
Four more years of reading and writing and digging and straining and growing and no-sleep and lots of migraines and margaritas and here I am – capped and gowned, official and done here, older and fuller, ready and not for the next wild unknown. As I hover in this in-between space where, once again, things don't fit together so obviously, I keep coming back to the words where I started, the words that acknowledge these rhythms, these curves in the road, willing my anthem to run through me, please run through me again,
.
"Potentially lovely/Perpetually human/Suspended and OPEN"
